    fig = plt.figure(1,figsize=(10,3))

    plt.xlabel('day')
    plt.ylabel('views')

The views on wiki pages seem very distinct without any distinguishing pattern. Some things to note are as follows:

  • Most pages have multiple spikes in views indicating sudden interest due to current events.
  • Some pages have zero views in the beginning, indicating that they might have been created within that range of dates (for e.g. Starboy).
  • Max views for some pages is >100,000 (e.g. US presidential election 1996) while others <1000 (e.g. Riley Keough).
  • There are some pages (e.g. Angela Bowie) which has >100,000 for one day while almost zero views for most other days.

The main takeaway from these plots is that the views on each page is different with unique pattern in spikes and a simple technique such as predicting the mean of views for the provided time period may not be a good strategy to forecast views.

2.3 Components of time series data¶

There are two types of components in time series data: systematic and non-systematic.

Systematic data is consistent, recurrent and can be described and model while non-systematic data cannot be modeled directly.

The components of time series data are as follows:

  1. Level: Average value in the series
  2. Trend: Increasing and decreasing value in the series
  3. Seasonality: repeating short-term cycle in the series
  4. Noise: random variation in the series.

While level, trend and seasonality are the systematic components. Noise is a non-systematic component of time series data.

There are three types of mpdels available to decompose time series data:

  1. Additive model:

     y(t) = Level + Trend + Seasonality + Noise

  2. Multiplicative model:

     y(t) = Level * Trend * Seasonality * Noise

  3. Pseudo-Additive model:

     y(t) = Trend * (Seasonality + Noise - 1)

Here we use the "seasonal_decompose" function from the statsmodel library and the additive model to visualize total daily views of spanish and english wiki pages:

In [397]:

3. Data Transformation¶

3.1 Removing outliers¶

We need to remove outliers from the time series because they result in artifical trends in data which in our case is usually because of some current events causing huge number of people to view a wiki page. For example, while exploring the dataset I found a wiki aritcle that had <100 views on all days expect one when it had 100,000+ hits. On further investigation, I found that the wiki page was that of an obscure pop artist, who had been caught in a drug related police investigation on that day resulting in huge traffic to his wiki page. ITs unrealistic to expect the model to predict such anomalies as they may not repeat on a periodic basis. It is best to remove such data points in order to get more prediction for web traffic.

In order to determine the outliers, an upper and lower bound is defined and any value outside that band is considered an outlier. The bounds are a combination of mean absolute error and deviation of the data, both of which are calculated around the rolling mean with frequency 7 days. The outliers are replaced by the upper or lower bound.

3.2 Normalization¶

In order to have a consistent range of data and be able to compare results between different time series, each time series is normalized between 0 and 1. The formula for normalizing the _i_th element of a series is

\begin{equation*} x_i = \frac{x_{i}-x_{min}}{x_{max}-x_{min}} \end{equation*}

The following function called "RemoveOutliers" removes outliers as well as normalizes the data and returns a series with outlier removed.

In [807]:
def RemoveOutliers(input, window, plot_intervals=False, scale=1, plot_anomalies=False):

    """
        series - dataframe with timeseries
        window - rolling window size 
        plot_intervals - show confidence intervals
        plot_anomalies - show anomalies 

    """
    series = input.copy()
    rolling_mean = series.rolling(window=window).mean()
    #print(rolling_mean)
    plt.figure(figsize=(15,5))
    plt.title("Moving average\n window size = {}".format(window))
    plt.plot(rolling_mean, "g", label="Rolling mean trend")

    # Plot confidence intervals for smoothed values
    if plot_intervals:
        mae = mean_absolute_error(series[window:], rolling_mean[window:])
        deviation = np.std(series[window:] - rolling_mean[window:])
        lower_bond = rolling_mean - (mae + scale * deviation)
        upper_bond = rolling_mean + (mae + scale * deviation)
        plt.plot(upper_bond, "r--", label="Upper Bound")
        plt.plot(lower_bond, "r--", label="Lower Bound")
        
        # Having the intervals, find abnormal values
        if plot_anomalies:
            #series[(series<lower_bond)|(series>upper_bond)] = upper_bond
            anomalies = []
            anomalies = series[(series<lower_bond)|(series>upper_bond)]
            series[series<lower_bond] = lower_bond
            series[series>upper_bond] = upper_bond
            #anomalies = pd.DataFrame(index=series.index)
            #anomalies[series<lower_bond] = series[series<lower_bond]
            #anomalies[series<lower_bond] = series.loc[series<lower_bond]
            #anomalies[series>upper_bond] = series[series>upper_bond]
            #print(anomalies)
            plt.plot(anomalies, "ro", markersize=10, label="Anomalies")
        
    plt.plot(series[window:], label="Actual values")
    plt.legend(loc="upper left")
    plt.grid(True)
    
    series=(series-series.min())/(series.max()-series.min()) #normalize data b/w 0 and 1
    series[series==0]=10**-6  #replace zero by by a non-zero low value
    return series

The following example shows data with outliers removed for total daily views of russian wiki pages. The red dots are the outliers, the green line is the rolling mean average, the broken lines are upper and lower bounds while the blue line is the data with outliers removed

4. Forecasting¶

4.1 Holt-Winter's Method (Triple exponential smoothing)¶

Exponential Smoothing methods predict future values based on the weighted average of current value and previous values. The triple exponential method takes into account the level, trend and seasonality of previous and current values to predict future points.

More detailed explanation of triple exponential smoothing with equations can be found here: https://www.itl.nist.gov/div898/handbook/pmc/section4/pmc435.htm

Holt_Prediction_function outputs the predictions using four methods:

    - additive seasonal
    - multiplicative seasonal
    - additive seasonal damped
    - multiplicative seasonal damped

A fifth method is used to benchmark our model. This benchmark is a "simple model" which predicts that the observation in the next n days will be the same as last n days.

The function takes time series data as input and breaks it into training and testing sets. The ratio of training to testing set is 3:1 i.e. it takes trains on 150 days of data and makes prediction on 50 days worth of data. The function then creates models by fitting the training data using the four methods mentioned above and a specified seasonal period (7 in our case). The function then makes predictions for 50 days using the model.

In [759]:
from statsmodels.tsa.holtwinters import ExponentialSmoothing

#Source: https://www.statsmodels.org/dev/examples/notebooks/generated/exponential_smoothing.html
        
def HoltWinters_Prediction_function(data):
    
    data.index = pd.to_datetime(data.index)
    data = data.asfreq('d')
    
    train, test = data.iloc[:100], data.iloc[100:]

    fit1 = ExponentialSmoothing(train, seasonal_periods=7, trend='add', seasonal='add').fit(use_boxcox=False)
    fit2 = ExponentialSmoothing(train, seasonal_periods=7, trend='add', seasonal='mul').fit(use_boxcox=False)
    fit3 = ExponentialSmoothing(train, seasonal_periods=7, trend='add', seasonal='add', damped=True).fit(use_boxcox=False)
    fit4 = ExponentialSmoothing(train, seasonal_periods=7, trend='add', seasonal='mul', damped=True).fit(use_boxcox=False)

    results=pd.DataFrame(index=[r"$\alpha$",r"$\beta$",r"$\phi$",r"$\gamma$",r"$l_0$","$b_0$","SSE"])

    params = ['smoothing_level', 'smoothing_slope', 'damping_slope', 'smoothing_seasonal', 'initial_level', 'initial_slope']

    results["Additive"]       = [fit1.params[p] for p in params] + [fit1.sse]
    results["Multiplicative"] = [fit2.params[p] for p in params] + [fit2.sse]
    results["Additive Dam"]   = [fit3.params[p] for p in params] + [fit3.sse]
    results["Multiplica Dam"] = [fit4.params[p] for p in params] + [fit4.sse]

    ax = data.plot(figsize=(10,6), color='black', title="Forecasts from Holt-Winters' multiplicative method" )
    ax.set_ylabel("Views")
    ax.set_xlabel("Days")
    #fit1.fittedvalues.plot(ax=ax, style='--', color='red')
    #fit2.fittedvalues.plot(ax=ax, style='--', color='green')
    #fit3.fittedvalues.plot(ax=ax, style='--', color='blue')
    #fit4.fittedvalues.plot(ax=ax, style='--', color='black')


    pred1 = fit1.predict(start=test.index[0], end=test.index[-1])
    pred2 = fit2.predict(start=test.index[0], end=test.index[-1])
    pred3 = fit3.predict(start=test.index[0], end=test.index[-1])
    pred4 = fit4.predict(start=test.index[0], end=test.index[-1])
    pred5 =  train.iloc[50:100]
    pred5.index = test.index
    
    pred1.rename('Holt-Winters (add-add-seasonal)').plot(ax=ax, style='--',  color='red', legend=True)
    pred2.rename('Holt-Winters (add-mul-seasonal)').plot(ax=ax, style='--', color='green', legend=True)
    pred3.rename('Holt-Winters (add-add-seasonal) - damped').plot(ax=ax, style='--',  color='blue', legend=True)
    pred4.rename('Holt-Winters (add-mul-seasonal) - damped').plot(ax=ax, style='--',  color='pink', legend=True)
    pred5.rename('Simple Model)').plot(ax=ax, style='--',  color='cyan', legend=True)

    plt.show()
    print("Forecasting views of wiki pages using Holt-Winters method with both additive and multiplicative seasonality.")

    results
    
    HoltWinters_Prediction = pd.concat([pred1, pred2, pred3, pred4,pred5], axis=1)
    #HoltWinters_Prediction.columns[4] = "5"
    #pd.DataFrame({'pred1': pred1, 'pred2': pred2, 'pred3': pred3, 'pred4': pred4})
    #for i in range(7):
    #   HoltWinters_r2score = HoltWinters_r2score.append({'add-seas': (r2_score(actual[i*7:(i+1)*7], prediction1[i*7:(i+1)*7])), 'mul-seas': (r2_score(actual[i*7:(i+1)*7], prediction2[i*7:(i+1)*7])), 'add-seas-dam': (r2_score(actual[i*7:(i+1)*7], prediction3[i*7:(i+1)*7])), 'mul-seas-dam': (r2_score(actual[i*7:(i+1)*7], prediction4[i*7:(i+1)*7]))}, ignore_index=True)
    
    return HoltWinters_Prediction

4.2 Evaluation metrics: Root Mean Square Error (RMSE)¶

Root Mean Square Error (RMSE) is used for evaluating the predictions made by the model. The mean squared error (MSE) is the average of the squared prediction errors. Squaring the error values gives a positive number and also puts more weight on large errors. RMSE is the root of MSE which has the same unit as the observations.

We create a function called HoltWinters_RMSE_Plot that takes the predicted values and plots the RMSE for predictions for every week. It also return a table with weekly errors from each of the 5 methods described in section 4.1

In [769]:
def HoltWinters_RMSE_Plot(actual,prediction_df,language):
    
    prediction1 = prediction_df[0]
    prediction2 = prediction_df[1]
    prediction3 = prediction_df[2]
    prediction4 = prediction_df[3]
    prediction5 = prediction_df.iloc[:,4]
    
    HoltWinters_RMSE = pd.DataFrame({'add-seas': [], 'mul-seas': [], 'add-seas-dam': [], 'mul-seas-dam': [], 'simple-model': []})
    for i in range(7):
        HoltWinters_RMSE = HoltWinters_RMSE.append({'add-seas': sqrt(mean_squared_error(actual[i*7:(i+1)*7], prediction1[i*7:(i+1)*7])), 'mul-seas': sqrt(mean_squared_error(actual[i*7:(i+1)*7], prediction2[i*7:(i+1)*7])), 'add-seas-dam': sqrt(mean_squared_error(actual[i*7:(i+1)*7], prediction3[i*7:(i+1)*7])), 'mul-seas-dam': sqrt(mean_squared_error(actual[i*7:(i+1)*7], prediction4[i*7:(i+1)*7])), 'simple-model': sqrt(mean_squared_error(actual[i*7:(i+1)*7], prediction5[i*7:(i+1)*7]))}, ignore_index=True)

    labels = ['add-seasonal', 'mul-seasonal', 'add-seas-damped', 'mul-seas-damped','simple-model']
    colors=['r','g','b','m','c']

    for i in range(0,5):
        plt.plot(HoltWinters_RMSE.iloc[:,i],'o-',color=colors[i],label=labels[i])
    
    plt.xlabel('week')
    plt.ylabel('RMSE')
    plt.title('RMSE for total daily views of '+language+ ' wiki pages \n using Holt-Winters exponential Smoothing\n')
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()
    
    return HoltWinters_RMSE
